nigd Koninkrijk","Laughton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Laughton, Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Laughton, Leicestershire, England":"Laughton, Leicestershire, England"},"en":{"1437–":"1437–Deceased","1435–1472":"1435–1472","1460–Male":"1460–Deceased","1462–Female":"1462–Deceased","1464–Male":"1464–Deceased","1466–Female":"1466–Deceased","1468–1541":"1468–1541","1470–Female":"1470–Deceased","1472–Male":"1472–Deceased","1474–Female":"1474–Deceased","1437–Female":"1437–Deceased","1462":"1462","1472":"1472","1460":"1460","1470":"1470","1437":"1437","1458":"1458","1468":"1468","1435":"1435","1466":"1466","1464":"1464","about 1468":"about 1468","1541":"1541","1474":"1474","about 1466":"about 1466","Laughton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Laughton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Laughton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Laughton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Laughton, Leicestershire, England":"Laughton, Leicestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alianore Beauchamp was born in 1437, in England, United Kingdom. She married John Knight in 1458, in Laughton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 4 daughters."},"et":{"1437–":"1437–Surnud","1435–1472":"1435–1472","1460–Male":"1460–Surnud","1462–Female":"1462–Surnud","1464–Male":"1464–Surnud","1466–Female":"1466–Surnud","1468–1541":"1468–1541","1